After an exhausting day of hoofing it up to 11,300' (~3400 m) above sea level, napping under the starry sky came easily. 
@ivanbland, taking a rest while being bathed by 26,000 year old starlight from the galactic core.

This photo doesn't quite do justice to the totality. Definitely one of those most cosmic experiences you can have without leaving the planet. Good job, sun and moon 🌞🌚

Right before totality, clouds rolled in but quickly dissipated. It was a good 90-degree and you can feel the temperature drop. What made it a bit eerie was the semi-darkness and periodic winds shaking the leaves. Reminded me of the movie 'The Happening".
Team Julia taking on the eclipse. We were pretty excited, can you tell? //

Happy Solar Eclipse 2017 from the Path of Totality! We took our 4WD adventure van and camper trailer up into the southern region of the Mt. Hood National Forest - up some super bumpy forest roads, just feet from the Pacific Crest Trail where no camper dared - but was rewarded with a perfect view of the sun and 100% totality. We brought our dog Gravy, our cat Biscuit, and the kids insisted I make eclipse glasses for all the stuffed toys they brought too. It was totality worth it. Road tripping like...

Here's a fun fact.
That "professional weekenders" thing in my bio? I wrote that 4 years ago when I had about 500 followers, worked a 9 to 5 Monday through Friday, and lived in an apartment in Salt Lake City.
It was never meant to imply that I didn't work or that life was one long weekend for Keith and I.
I wrote it because being a "weekend warrior" was something I was so dedicated to, I actually treated it like a 2nd job.
I packed up my crap every. single. Friday. and drove through the night to get somewhere new or somewhere quiet or somewhere I'd been 100 times.
Sometimes we drove for 2 hours, other times we drove for 8, falling asleep in the back of Keith's pickup truck or a poorly assembled tent...knowing full well that we had to be back by Monday morning.
Sure there were plenty of days that I was tired and could have just gone home and watched TV instead.
But I didn't.
So please don't buy into this idea that adventure and travel is only for the "Vanlifers" or the Instagram sponsored kids...that it only entails 5 star hotels and airline tickets...or that it costs a ton of money.
Instead, I ask you to go pull up your house on Google earth, then map a circle around it that spans 5 hours drive time in every direction. What do you see?
If you left work at 5pm, how many places could you be by 10?
So buy an adventure calendar and make a list and pack a bag and tell your friends and then GO.
I say this to you not as the girl who lives in her van...not as the girl with all the Instagram followers...not as the girl with all the time in the world to roam about...
I say this to you as the girl who sat for years with a backpack under her desk at her cubicle waiting for the clock to strike 5.
Get out there, kids.
There's a whole world to see.

Today @rei launches an initiative called #ForceOfNature to create opportunities for women in the outdoors and to put women front and center in all our storytelling. As an #REIemployee and having had a tiny part of this about a year ago in some focus groups, it's so great to see this come to life and shine a light on bringing us all together in the world's largest level playing field -- the outdoors. As my friend @romanianmagician so eloquently put it -- "Imagine a world free of 'shoulds' and 'supposed tos' through a relationship with the outdoors, and the impact that could have on identity, adventures, dreams and potential FOR US ALL." Check out more at www.rei.com/forceofnature 🏔💃🏽🌲
